DENNIS FREEMAN:
Hello and welcome.

00:00:28.110 --> 00:00:30.627
Today, we're starting the
second half of the class.

00:00:30.627 --> 00:00:32.210
In the second half
of the class, we'll

00:00:32.210 --> 00:00:35.330
focus on methods that
will generally be

00:00:35.330 --> 00:00:38.480
described as Fourier methods.

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:45.060
And those methods revolve
around thinking about signals

00:00:45.060 --> 00:00:47.719
as being sums of sine waves.

00:00:47.719 --> 00:00:49.260
So we've previously
thought about how

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:53.030
you can think about a
system by thinking about how

00:00:53.030 --> 00:00:54.690
it responds to sine waves.

00:00:54.690 --> 00:00:57.630
So this is closely related.

00:00:57.630 --> 00:01:01.130
Now, instead of
thinking about a system

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:06.570
by how it processes
these sine waves.

00:01:06.570 --> 00:01:09.230
Rather, we'll
think about signals

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:11.166
as being composed of sine waves.

00:01:11.166 --> 00:01:12.290
So that's sort of the idea.

00:01:12.290 --> 00:01:14.660
And today, we'll do
the very simplest kind

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:18.380
of representation, which
is a Fourier series.

00:01:18.380 --> 00:01:21.320
The importance of that's going
to be our first encounter

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:25.850
with how you can think
about complicated signals

00:01:25.850 --> 00:01:27.980
as sums of sines and cosines.

00:01:27.980 --> 00:01:29.840
But also, we'll get
a new representation

00:01:29.840 --> 00:01:33.000
for a system that
will be generally

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.430
useful called a filter.

00:01:35.430 --> 00:01:37.140
So that's the two
agenda items for today.

00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:42.090
Roughly, the first half
is on the Fourier series

00:01:42.090 --> 00:01:44.370
representations for a signal.

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:47.460
The second half is on
thinking about systems

00:01:47.460 --> 00:01:51.540
as filters, which is a direct
consequence of the first.

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:54.480
So the first idea is
just, why should we

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:56.610
even think that you
can think about signals

00:01:56.610 --> 00:01:58.020
in terms of sine waves?

00:01:58.020 --> 00:02:01.200
Well, there's very
simple examples of that.

00:02:01.200 --> 00:02:04.440
Some signals are just very
naturally described that way.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:08.699
One class of those are the ones
whose entire frequency content

00:02:08.699 --> 00:02:11.120
are harmonics.

00:02:11.120 --> 00:02:15.180
Just a bit of jargon, we'll
think about harmonics of omega

00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:18.020
0, harmonics of some frequency.

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:21.110
Say, 1 kilohertz.

00:02:21.110 --> 00:02:22.740
Then we'll have
the first harmonic.

00:02:22.740 --> 00:02:25.860
That's another name
for the fundamental.

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:28.440
That's 1 kilohertz, for example.

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:30.810
Second harmonic would
be some component

00:02:30.810 --> 00:02:32.020
at twice the frequency.

00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:33.790
Third harmonic, three
times the frequency.

00:02:33.790 --> 00:02:38.730
0-th harmonic for
the completely--

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:40.890
so for no good
reason at all, we'll

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:44.370
call them 0-th
harmonic the DC term,

00:02:44.370 --> 00:02:46.530
meaning Direct Current,
which is neither direct

00:02:46.530 --> 00:02:48.360
nor has anything
to do with current.

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:51.910
But we will use that jargon
because everybody else does.

00:02:51.910 --> 00:02:54.250
So that's just jargon.

00:02:54.250 --> 00:02:57.340
What I want to think about
though at a deeper level is,

00:02:57.340 --> 00:02:59.780
what kinds of signals
should we expect

00:02:59.780 --> 00:03:02.820
have a good
representation in terms

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:04.770
of sums of sines and cosines?

00:03:04.770 --> 00:03:09.060
And one very easy kind of
signal that you can think about

00:03:09.060 --> 00:03:13.450
is signals that we associate
with musical instruments.

00:03:13.450 --> 00:03:17.330
So think about the sounds that
these instruments generate.

