00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:05.600
And there's a different
relationship here.

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:07.900
So what I want you to do
is to hear the difference

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:10.810
between those six sounds.

00:07:10.810 --> 00:07:14.090
And again, think about not
only the time waveform,

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:17.323
but also how their
harmonics relate.

00:07:17.323 --> 00:07:20.774
[PLAYING NOTES]

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:45.190
So dissonance has something
to do-- well, consonance

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:48.164
has something to
do with the overlap

00:07:48.164 --> 00:07:49.830
of the harmonic
structure and dissonance

00:07:49.830 --> 00:07:53.630
has something to do
with the lack of overlap

00:07:53.630 --> 00:07:55.280
of the harmonic content.

00:07:55.280 --> 00:07:58.850
So the point just being that
we can get some mileage out

00:07:58.850 --> 00:08:02.880
of thinking about
signals according

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:05.490
to their harmonic decomposition.

00:08:05.490 --> 00:08:08.769
So that's kind of
the introduction.

00:08:08.769 --> 00:08:10.060
How should we think about that?

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:14.650
What kinds of signals
ought to be representable

00:08:14.650 --> 00:08:16.550
by their harmonic structure?

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:17.050
OK.

00:08:17.050 --> 00:08:19.300
Well if you just draw a
picture in a time domain

00:08:19.300 --> 00:08:23.270
and think about a
fundamental, what would it

00:08:23.270 --> 00:08:24.827
look like in the time domain?

00:08:24.827 --> 00:08:26.160
What would the signal look like?

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:28.710
What would the second
harmonic look like?

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:34.299
Well, that's a signal whose
frequency is twice as big.

00:08:34.299 --> 00:08:37.850
If the frequency is twice as
big, the period is half as big.

00:08:37.850 --> 00:08:42.880
So there's now two periods of
the blue guy in the same time

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:47.020
interval as one
period of the red guy.

00:08:47.020 --> 00:08:51.040
So the relationship of
frequencies in the harmonics

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:54.910
has a relationship in time.

00:08:54.910 --> 00:08:56.860
It's inversely proportional.

00:08:56.860 --> 00:08:57.640
OK.

00:08:57.640 --> 00:09:01.370
So if you think about
fundamental, second, third,

00:09:01.370 --> 00:09:02.140
fourth, fifth.

00:09:02.140 --> 00:09:04.240
Fundamental, second,
third, fourth, fifth.

00:09:04.240 --> 00:09:10.270
There's a relationship
in time of the periods.

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:12.190
And one thing that
should be clear

00:09:12.190 --> 00:09:17.590
is that these harmonics are
all periodic in the period

00:09:17.590 --> 00:09:20.480
of the fundamental.

00:09:20.480 --> 00:09:22.490
So one thing that
you can think about,

00:09:22.490 --> 00:09:24.860
by thinking about the time
representation of what

00:09:24.860 --> 00:09:29.860
harmonic signals ought to
look like, periodic signals

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:33.070
are sort of our only candidates.

00:09:33.070 --> 00:09:37.120
All of the harmonics
of a fundamental

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:39.300
will have the same--

00:09:39.300 --> 00:09:43.990
are periodic in capital T,
the period of the fundamental.

00:09:43.990 --> 00:09:45.760
So it's going to
be hard to generate

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:48.610
a signal by a sum
of harmonics that

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:51.580
doesn't have that periodicity.

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:55.120
So we should be expecting a
relationship between signals

00:09:55.120 --> 00:09:58.660
that can be represented
by a sum of harmonics

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:00.230
and periodic signals.

00:10:03.320 --> 00:10:06.640
So we would not expect
an aperiodic signal

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:08.770
to be represented this way.

00:10:08.770 --> 00:10:11.170
The counter question
is, should we

00:10:11.170 --> 00:10:14.770
be expecting that all periodic
signals can be represented

00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:16.990
this way, or some
periodic signals,

00:10:16.990 --> 00:10:18.835
or some very special class?

00:10:18.835 --> 00:10:20.600
Is it a big class
or a small class?

00:10:20.600 --> 00:10:22.450
How do we think about that?

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:24.850
And historically, that's
been a hard question.

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:27.640
And by the end of the hour, I
hope that you all understand

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:28.765
why it was a hard question.

00:10:31.300 --> 00:10:34.360
People, like Fourier,
you might imagine,

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:37.780
advocated the
notion that you can

00:10:37.780 --> 00:10:42.580
make a meaningful harmonic
representation for a very

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:44.230
wide class of signals.

00:10:44.230 --> 00:10:47.140
Fourier claimed,
basically, everything.

00:10:47.140 --> 00:10:50.080
Anything that was periodic
could be represented

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:52.210
in terms of a sum of harmonics.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:55.390
Other people thought
that was preposterous.

00:10:55.390 --> 00:10:59.950
In a widely reported
public rebuke of Fourier,

00:10:59.950 --> 00:11:03.010
Lagrange said,
this is ridiculous,

00:11:03.010 --> 00:11:09.330
because every harmonic is a
continuous function of time.

00:11:09.330 --> 00:11:12.250
And you can easily
manufacture a periodic signal

00:11:12.250 --> 00:11:15.510
that's a discontinuous
function of time.

00:11:15.510 --> 00:11:18.540
So for example, a square wave.

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:20.610
How on earth are you--

00:11:20.610 --> 00:11:25.090
Lagrange, how on earth
would you represent

00:11:25.090 --> 00:11:27.640
a discontinuous function by a
sum of continuous functions?

00:11:27.640 --> 00:11:30.130
That makes no sense.

00:11:30.130 --> 00:11:34.900
So what we will want to do
in the course of the hour

00:11:34.900 --> 00:11:37.730
is think about, does that
or doesn't that make sense?

00:11:37.730 --> 00:11:41.320
And it will turn out the
answer is kind of complicated.

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:43.000
And so we can sort
of forgive both sides

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.580
for having sort of
argued with each other

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:48.790
because the answer is
not completely obvious.

00:11:48.790 --> 00:11:50.890
For the time being, I'm
going to just assume

00:11:50.890 --> 00:11:55.830
that the answer is yes,
that it makes sense

00:11:55.830 --> 00:11:59.790
to try to make a harmonic
representation of a signal that

00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:01.200
might even be discontinuous.

00:12:01.200 --> 00:12:05.190
I'm going to assume
periodic, let's try.

00:12:05.190 --> 00:12:07.350
And the question will be,
does that make any sense?

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:12.520
So there's a little bit of math.

00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:13.960
There's a mathematical
foundation

00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:18.220
that makes understanding these
Fourier series very easy.

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:21.380
The idea has two parts.

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:26.650
First off, if you have a
sinusoidally-varying signal

00:12:26.650 --> 00:12:32.110
here at frequency k omega
0, the k-th harmonic.

00:12:32.110 --> 00:12:33.910
If you were to multiply
the k-th harmonic

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:40.880
times the l-th harmonic, a
signal of frequency k omega 0

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:43.790
times a signal of
frequency l omega 0,

00:12:43.790 --> 00:12:48.200
you get a new harmonic,
the k plus l-th one.

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:51.500
That's a simple property
of the way the product

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:53.540
of two exponents--

00:12:53.540 --> 00:12:55.850
you add the exponents
when you take the product

00:12:55.850 --> 00:12:58.190
of two exponentials.

00:12:58.190 --> 00:13:00.230
OK.

00:13:00.230 --> 00:13:02.990
So that makes it very easy to
think about harmonic structure

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:06.860
because there's a simple
relationship for generating

00:13:06.860 --> 00:13:10.370
one harmonic signal in
time from another harmonic

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:13.190
signal in time.

00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:15.010
The second thing
that makes harmonics

00:13:15.010 --> 00:13:17.950
easy to think about
mathematically

00:13:17.950 --> 00:13:19.940
is that if you integrate
over a period--

00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:23.696
we'll do this so often that
we'll abbreviate it this way.

00:13:23.696 --> 00:13:25.570
Because if you have a
signal that's periodic,

00:13:25.570 --> 00:13:27.550
it really doesn't
matter which period you

00:13:27.550 --> 00:13:29.920
choose to do the integral over.

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:33.670
If you had a signal that was
periodic in, say, capital T,

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:36.035
and integrated it between 0
and T. And if it's periodic,

00:13:36.035 --> 00:13:37.660
you should be able
to shift that window

00:13:37.660 --> 00:13:41.810
anywhere you like and you
should get the same thing.

00:13:41.810 --> 00:13:46.450
So we'll not worry about whether
it goes from 0 to capital T

00:13:46.450 --> 00:13:49.397
or from 1 to capital T plus 1.

00:13:49.397 --> 00:13:50.480
We won't worry about that.

00:13:50.480 --> 00:13:53.680
We'll just say integrate
over the period T.

00:13:53.680 --> 00:14:00.430
If you integrate over the
period T any harmonic signal,

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:03.800
then there's only
two possible answers.

00:14:03.800 --> 00:14:05.750
So if you integrate
e to the jk omega

00:14:05.750 --> 00:14:12.690
0 T over one period
of omega 0, there

00:14:12.690 --> 00:14:16.310
will be k periods in there.

00:14:16.310 --> 00:14:20.490
So if k is a number
other than 0,

00:14:20.490 --> 00:14:23.050
you'll have complete
periods of a sine wave.

00:14:23.050 --> 00:14:26.010
So the answer of the
integral, the average value

00:14:26.010 --> 00:14:29.310
over that period, is 0.

00:14:29.310 --> 00:14:32.190
The only time you'll ever
get something that's non-zero

00:14:32.190 --> 00:14:35.130
is if k were 0.

00:14:35.130 --> 00:14:40.640
If k were 0, if it were
DC, then e to the 0 is 1.

00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:43.400
The integral of 1 over a period,
regardless of what period

00:14:43.400 --> 00:14:45.650
you pick up, the integral
of 1 over a period

00:14:45.650 --> 00:14:50.180
is capital T. So two things.

00:14:50.180 --> 00:14:52.600
It's easy to figure
out the product

00:14:52.600 --> 00:14:54.100
of two harmonic signals.

00:14:54.100 --> 00:14:55.690
It's just the
different harmonic.

00:14:55.690 --> 00:14:59.320
And integrals over
a period are easy.

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:02.830
With that basis, then
it's easy to say how--

00:15:02.830 --> 00:15:06.610
let's imagine that some
arbitrary periodic signal,

00:15:06.610 --> 00:15:09.940
which we can always write this
way, x of t, if it's periodic,

