00:27:49.312 --> 00:27:50.020
All of the above?

00:27:50.020 --> 00:27:51.730
Obviously not.

00:27:51.730 --> 00:27:55.450
The point is it's simple
to do and you end up

00:27:55.450 --> 00:28:06.270
representing the time waveform
by just a sequence of numbers.

00:28:06.270 --> 00:28:07.950
How big is the fundamental?

00:28:07.950 --> 00:28:09.270
How big is the second harmonic?

00:28:09.270 --> 00:28:13.170
How big is the third
harmonic, et cetera.

00:28:13.170 --> 00:28:17.130
There's some more math that
makes things even easier.

00:28:17.130 --> 00:28:22.600
There are ways of thinking
about operations in time

00:28:22.600 --> 00:28:26.860
as equivalent
operations in harmonics.

00:28:26.860 --> 00:28:29.310
That makes the idea
even more powerful

00:28:29.310 --> 00:28:31.120
because what we
are developing is

00:28:31.120 --> 00:28:34.300
an alternative
representation for signals.

00:28:34.300 --> 00:28:38.000
The same as we had multiple
representations for systems--

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:41.180
differential equations, block
diagrams, h of t, h of s,

00:28:41.180 --> 00:28:45.350
h of r, Bode plots, all those
different representations

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:49.940
of systems, this represents
an alternative representation

00:28:49.940 --> 00:28:51.320
of a signal.

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:53.810
We think about it being
represented in time

00:28:53.810 --> 00:28:57.170
or we think about it being
represented in harmonics.

00:28:57.170 --> 00:28:59.634
Or eventually, we'll
call that frequency.

00:28:59.634 --> 00:29:01.550
So we'll think about
signals being represented

00:29:01.550 --> 00:29:02.894
in time or frequency.

00:29:02.894 --> 00:29:04.310
And you can think
about operations

00:29:04.310 --> 00:29:08.980
in time having a corresponding
operation in frequency.

00:29:08.980 --> 00:29:12.520
So illustrated here, if a signal
is differentiated in time,

00:29:12.520 --> 00:29:18.340
the Fourier coefficients are
multiplied by j 2 pi over T k.

00:29:18.340 --> 00:29:19.690
OK, well that's easy.

00:29:19.690 --> 00:29:21.370
If we assume for
the moment that we

00:29:21.370 --> 00:29:25.160
can represent x as
this kind of a sum,

00:29:25.160 --> 00:29:27.530
differentiation is linear.

00:29:27.530 --> 00:29:30.510
The derivative of a sum is
the sum of the derivatives.

00:29:30.510 --> 00:29:32.930
The derivative of
sine wave is easy.

00:29:32.930 --> 00:29:39.310
And we end up with the idea that
if you knew the a sub k's, then

00:29:39.310 --> 00:29:45.460
you can easily formulate
the series representation

00:29:45.460 --> 00:29:48.250
for the harmonic
structure by just

00:29:48.250 --> 00:29:52.795
multiplying each of the ak's
by the power of the exponent.

00:29:55.740 --> 00:29:56.240
OK.

00:29:56.240 --> 00:30:01.770
So that gives us a way of
thinking about signals in time

00:30:01.770 --> 00:30:05.050
as being represented
in frequency.

00:30:05.050 --> 00:30:07.520
So here's an
illustration of that.

