00:33:47.650 --> 00:33:48.640
Is it real-valued?

00:33:48.640 --> 00:33:52.710
Well, now it is because
I had a j times j.

00:33:52.710 --> 00:33:56.547
So now they are real-valued.

00:33:56.547 --> 00:33:57.880
Does it decrease with k squared?

00:33:57.880 --> 00:33:59.920
Now it does because
I got one of the k's

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:02.410
from the differentiation
operator and the other k

00:34:02.410 --> 00:34:04.504
from over here.

00:34:04.504 --> 00:34:05.170
Infinite number.

00:34:05.170 --> 00:34:06.310
Of course, the old one did, too.

00:34:06.310 --> 00:34:07.018
All of the above?

00:34:07.018 --> 00:34:08.031
Yes.

00:34:08.031 --> 00:34:08.530
OK.

00:34:08.530 --> 00:34:12.460
So that was just supposed to
be a simple exercise in how

00:34:12.460 --> 00:34:17.530
to run the formulas, how to
do the stuff from a purely

00:34:17.530 --> 00:34:19.940
mechanical point of view.

00:34:19.940 --> 00:34:23.620
Now I want to think about
the bigger question.

00:34:23.620 --> 00:34:26.260
Does any of this make any sense?

00:34:26.260 --> 00:34:30.670
And the answers were concocted
to help me make sense of that.

00:34:30.670 --> 00:34:32.440
The questions, the
check yourselves,

00:34:32.440 --> 00:34:35.500
were concocted so that if we
think about the answer that

00:34:35.500 --> 00:34:38.020
came out, we will
have some insight

00:34:38.020 --> 00:34:42.040
into why we think it works
and why it was controversial

00:34:42.040 --> 00:34:45.100
150 years ago.

00:34:45.100 --> 00:34:47.370
So let's do the
simple case first.

00:34:47.370 --> 00:34:50.550
Even Lagrange wouldn't have
any trouble with this-- well,

00:34:50.550 --> 00:34:52.889
maybe he would have
had a little trouble.

00:34:52.889 --> 00:34:55.320
I guess he would have
had a little trouble.

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:58.620
So Lagrange had the
problem with Fourier

00:34:58.620 --> 00:35:00.900
that Fourier was making
these outrageous claims

00:35:00.900 --> 00:35:03.200
that any periodic function
should have a Fourier

00:35:03.200 --> 00:35:03.790
decomposition.

00:35:03.790 --> 00:35:06.390
And if you have a
discontinuous function,

00:35:06.390 --> 00:35:08.580
and if all the basis
functions are continuous,

00:35:08.580 --> 00:35:11.310
how could that make any sense?

00:35:11.310 --> 00:35:13.200
This doesn't have
any discontinuities,

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:17.612
but it does have
slope discontinuities.

00:35:17.612 --> 00:35:19.276
That's sort of the same thing.

00:35:19.276 --> 00:35:20.650
If you have a
slope discontinuity

00:35:20.650 --> 00:35:22.590
and you're trying to make--

00:35:22.590 --> 00:35:26.530
you're trying to represent the
signal by a sum of signals,

00:35:26.530 --> 00:35:30.010
none of whom have slope
discontinuities, that's kind

00:35:30.010 --> 00:35:31.960
of the same kind of problem.

00:35:31.960 --> 00:35:34.090
One way we can think
about it is to think

00:35:34.090 --> 00:35:38.860
about how the approximation
gets better, or fails

00:35:38.860 --> 00:35:42.302
to get better, as we add terms.

00:35:42.302 --> 00:35:43.510
So this is the base function.

00:35:43.510 --> 00:35:47.020
This is the signal that we would
like to represent harmonically.

00:35:47.020 --> 00:35:53.380
If we just think about
the first non-zero term,

00:35:53.380 --> 00:35:55.930
the first non-zero term
is the fundamental.

00:35:55.930 --> 00:35:58.420
It actually is not bad.

00:35:58.420 --> 00:36:01.780
If we were willing to accept
errors about this big,

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:04.280
it would be OK.

00:36:04.280 --> 00:36:08.590
But somehow, it doesn't
capture much triangliness.

00:36:08.590 --> 00:36:10.940
It sort of doesn't
look much [INAUDIBLE]..

00:36:10.940 --> 00:36:14.380
So the one term sort of
catches a lot of the deviation,

00:36:14.380 --> 00:36:17.230
but it doesn't capture
the triangle aspect.

00:36:17.230 --> 00:36:18.940
If you add another term--

00:36:18.940 --> 00:36:21.940
the next non-zero
term is the third one.

00:36:21.940 --> 00:36:25.780
So if you write the sum of the
first term, the k equals 1 term

00:36:25.780 --> 00:36:30.420
and the k equals 3 term,
you get this waveform.

00:36:30.420 --> 00:36:32.780
Notice that the effect
of that was to creep it

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:36.390
toward the underlying signal.

00:36:36.390 --> 00:36:37.830
If you add another term--

00:36:37.830 --> 00:36:43.780
5, 7, 9-- it's getting
closer, closer, closer.

00:36:43.780 --> 00:36:46.420
19 because I got bored
making the figures,

00:36:46.420 --> 00:36:49.410
so I skipped a bunch.

00:36:49.410 --> 00:36:52.920
29, because I skipped a bunch.

00:36:52.920 --> 00:36:54.500
39.

00:36:54.500 --> 00:36:55.880
You can see that
what's happening

00:36:55.880 --> 00:36:59.840
is as we add more and
more of those terms,

00:36:59.840 --> 00:37:03.089
by the time we got up to
number 39, it's pretty good.

00:37:03.089 --> 00:37:05.630
So that probably from your seat,
it's not altogether apparent

00:37:05.630 --> 00:37:06.588
that they're different.

00:37:06.588 --> 00:37:08.330
They're still different.

00:37:08.330 --> 00:37:12.800
But you can see that
there is a sense

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:14.900
in which the approximation
is converging

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:19.340
toward the underlying signal.

00:37:19.340 --> 00:37:21.150
That's good.

00:37:21.150 --> 00:37:23.370
So that's a sense
in which there is

00:37:23.370 --> 00:37:27.853
a convergence between the signal
and its Fourier representation.

00:37:33.276 --> 00:37:37.310
A different kind of
thing happens here.

00:37:37.310 --> 00:37:39.910
Now, let's do the square wave.

00:37:39.910 --> 00:37:44.500
If we put in the first term
of the Fourier representation,

00:37:44.500 --> 00:37:48.380
which is the fundamental, we
get a sine wave approximation

00:37:48.380 --> 00:37:50.740
which is a little worse
perhaps for a square wave

00:37:50.740 --> 00:37:53.980
than it was for a triangle wave.

00:37:53.980 --> 00:38:02.150
Put in the 3rd, 5th,
7th, 9th, 19th--

00:38:02.150 --> 00:38:05.610
so I threw in 5 again--

00:38:05.610 --> 00:38:07.620
29, 39.

00:38:10.350 --> 00:38:12.039
It's not doing as well.

00:38:12.039 --> 00:38:13.080
What's not doing as well?

00:38:19.250 --> 00:38:24.600
So we go one-term partial sum--

00:38:24.600 --> 00:38:30.230
2, 3, 4, 5, 20.

00:38:30.230 --> 00:38:33.850
10, 15, 20.

00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:34.830
Yeah.

00:38:34.830 --> 00:38:36.300
AUDIENCE: It's
not able to handle

00:38:36.300 --> 00:38:38.115
the really quick transitions.

00:38:38.115 --> 00:38:39.740
DENNIS FREEMAN: It's
not able to handle

00:38:39.740 --> 00:38:41.090
the really quick transition.

00:38:41.090 --> 00:38:43.971
It's kind of like
Lagrange said, right?

00:38:43.971 --> 00:38:46.220
How are you going to make a
discontinuous function out

00:38:46.220 --> 00:38:47.870
of a sum of continuous ones?

00:38:47.870 --> 00:38:49.720
It's hard.

00:38:49.720 --> 00:38:53.790
In fact, this is
called Gibbs phenomena,

00:38:53.790 --> 00:38:56.040
after the guy who
sort of formulated

00:38:56.040 --> 00:38:59.820
the mathematics of this.

00:38:59.820 --> 00:39:02.310
Even in the limit, no
matter how many terms

00:39:02.310 --> 00:39:08.250
you put into the sum, the worst
case deviation is about 9%.

00:39:11.060 --> 00:39:13.260
You can't get rid of it.

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:18.900
So in some sense,
Lagrange is right.

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:21.690
You can't put enough
terms in there

00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:25.320
so that it converges everywhere.

00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:28.020
So the problem then becomes
that we can't really

00:39:28.020 --> 00:39:30.360
think about convergence in
the familiar ways we like

00:39:30.360 --> 00:39:31.710
to think about convergence.

00:39:31.710 --> 00:39:35.060
Convergence at a point is not
a good way to think about it.

00:39:35.060 --> 00:39:37.370
Because there's always a
point that deviates a lot.

00:39:39.920 --> 00:39:41.870
And in fact, in
signal processing

00:39:41.870 --> 00:39:46.040
we have lots of other ways
we think about convergence.

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:50.120
So in addition to being
9% overshoot, the Gibbs

00:39:50.120 --> 00:39:53.850
phenomenon, what else
do you see as the trend

00:39:53.850 --> 00:39:56.850
as you increase the number
of terms in the partial sum?

00:40:03.070 --> 00:40:06.580
In addition to
converging and staying

00:40:06.580 --> 00:40:10.610
sort of the same
height, what else

00:40:10.610 --> 00:40:12.720
happened as I added
terms to the partial sum?

00:40:17.690 --> 00:40:18.840
It got skinnier.

00:40:21.780 --> 00:40:26.430
The deviations got crammed
toward the transition point.

00:40:26.430 --> 00:40:27.900
And if I keep
adding them, they'll

00:40:27.900 --> 00:40:30.840
get crammed more
and more in there.

00:40:30.840 --> 00:40:32.610
And it's not like an impulse.

00:40:32.610 --> 00:40:34.380
The height didn't get bigger.

00:40:34.380 --> 00:40:37.032
The width got smaller.

00:40:37.032 --> 00:40:39.240
Had the height got bigger,
we'd have been in trouble.

00:40:41.860 --> 00:40:43.360
Because then we
would have said it

00:40:43.360 --> 00:40:45.940
deviates from the
square wave by having

00:40:45.940 --> 00:40:47.980
an impulse at the transition.

00:40:47.980 --> 00:40:49.880
It doesn't have an impulse.

00:40:49.880 --> 00:40:51.130
The height's staying the same.

00:40:51.130 --> 00:40:53.140
The width is smashing towards 0.

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:57.450
The energy in that signal is
getting smaller and smaller.

00:40:57.450 --> 00:41:00.650
So a different way to
think about convergence

00:41:00.650 --> 00:41:03.860
is, how big is the energy
difference between the two

00:41:03.860 --> 00:41:06.060
signals?

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:10.350
In that sense, this converges
and Fourier's right.

00:41:10.350 --> 00:41:14.280
As you add terms, the energy
difference between the two

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:16.950
signals goes to 0.

00:41:16.950 --> 00:41:21.600
That's the modern way of
thinking about the controversy.

00:41:21.600 --> 00:41:24.060
There is an issue.

00:41:24.060 --> 00:41:26.520
If we choose to think
about convergence

00:41:26.520 --> 00:41:28.950
in terms of energy
difference, then we

00:41:28.950 --> 00:41:30.330
can resolve the problem.

00:41:30.330 --> 00:41:32.970
That's what we'll do.

00:41:32.970 --> 00:41:36.060
That's the reason in lots of
the things that we talk about,

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:39.750
we haven't been too worried
about single points being off

00:41:39.750 --> 00:41:42.106
of curves.

00:41:42.106 --> 00:41:43.730
That's come up in
some of the homeworks

00:41:43.730 --> 00:41:45.790
that we don't really
care too much that--

00:41:45.790 --> 00:41:50.900
say you have a function that is
1 everywhere except one point.

00:41:50.900 --> 00:41:53.900
There's no energy difference
between the signal that differs

00:41:53.900 --> 00:41:56.058
by 1 point and the original.

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:01.990
It has a finite height,
but there's 0 width.

00:42:01.990 --> 00:42:04.060
So there's no energy difference.

00:42:04.060 --> 00:42:07.330
So that's the reason we haven't
been so worried about that

00:42:07.330 --> 00:42:11.732
because we use this kind of
a definition of equality.

00:42:11.732 --> 00:42:14.190
They're equal if there's no
energy difference between them.

00:42:17.650 --> 00:42:19.900
And using that kind of a way
of thinking about things,

00:42:19.900 --> 00:42:23.740
we get to write
Fourier decompositions,

00:42:23.740 --> 00:42:26.980
harmonic decompositions,
for a wide range of signals.

00:42:26.980 --> 00:42:28.360
Not all of them, right?

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:30.980
Fourier exaggerated.

00:42:30.980 --> 00:42:33.560
But for a wide range of signals.

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:35.970
In fact, the definition
we will typically use,

00:42:35.970 --> 00:42:41.690
is signals with finite energy
we'll be able to do this.

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:44.540
So now what I want to do is
the last part of this lecture,

00:42:44.540 --> 00:42:47.885
I want to introduce how
thinking about a signal in terms

00:42:47.885 --> 00:42:49.510
of its harmonic
structure lets us think

00:42:49.510 --> 00:42:53.940
about systems differently.

00:42:53.940 --> 00:42:56.300
So here, the idea
is we previously

00:42:56.300 --> 00:42:59.420
thought about systems
as frequency responses.

00:42:59.420 --> 00:43:02.270
In a frequency response, we
use the eigenfunction property.

00:43:02.270 --> 00:43:05.270
You put in an eigenfunction, one
of these complex exponentials.

00:43:05.270 --> 00:43:07.040
You get out the same
complex exponential

00:43:07.040 --> 00:43:10.040
if the system is
linear time invariant.

00:43:10.040 --> 00:43:12.555
And the eigenvalue is the
value of the system function

00:43:12.555 --> 00:43:14.180
evaluated at the
frequency of interest.

00:43:14.180 --> 00:43:16.570
We've done that before.

00:43:16.570 --> 00:43:19.450
The neat thing that happens if
you think about Fourier series

00:43:19.450 --> 00:43:21.430
is that you can
break down the input

00:43:21.430 --> 00:43:26.270
into a sum of discrete parts.

00:43:26.270 --> 00:43:28.780
The first harmonic, the 0-th
harmonic, the second harmonic,

00:43:28.780 --> 00:43:29.710
the third harmonic.

00:43:29.710 --> 00:43:34.510
And now, each one of those
parts was an eigenfunction.

00:43:34.510 --> 00:43:38.740
And each one of those parts
gets preferentially amplified

00:43:38.740 --> 00:43:43.810
and/or time-delayed according
to the frequency response

00:43:43.810 --> 00:43:46.820
idea for the system.

00:43:46.820 --> 00:43:50.180
That lets us think about
the effect of a system

00:43:50.180 --> 00:43:52.460
is to filter the input.

00:43:55.730 --> 00:43:59.810
The idea in a filter is
that systems do not--

00:43:59.810 --> 00:44:01.910
LTI systems, Linear
Time Invariant systems--

00:44:01.910 --> 00:44:03.951
the same kind of systems
that we've been thinking

00:44:03.951 --> 00:44:05.060
about all along so far.

00:44:05.060 --> 00:44:08.778
Linear time invariant systems
cannot create new frequencies.

00:44:11.650 --> 00:44:13.660
If you put some
frequency in, that's

00:44:13.660 --> 00:44:15.690
the frequency that comes out.

00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:19.500
We've already seen that when we
talk about frequency response.

00:44:19.500 --> 00:44:22.815
They can only scale the
magnitude and shift the phase.

00:44:22.815 --> 00:44:24.907
They can't make new
frequencies all they can do

00:44:24.907 --> 00:44:26.490
is change the amplitude
and the phase.

00:44:26.490 --> 00:44:29.890
And that's a very interesting
way to think about a system.

00:44:29.890 --> 00:44:32.340
Think about a low-pass filter.

00:44:32.340 --> 00:44:34.980
Think about a system
whose input is little vi

00:44:34.980 --> 00:44:36.900
and whose output is little vo.

00:44:36.900 --> 00:44:39.192
You all know how to characterize
that a gazillion ways.

00:44:39.192 --> 00:44:41.733
You would know how to write a
differential equation for that.

00:44:41.733 --> 00:44:42.680
Nod your head yes.

00:44:42.680 --> 00:44:43.730
Yes, yes, yes?

00:44:43.730 --> 00:44:46.230
You would know how to write
that as a differential equation.

00:44:46.230 --> 00:44:47.580
You'd be able to write
a system function.

00:44:47.580 --> 00:44:49.830
You'd be able to do a frequency
response, a Bode plot,

00:44:49.830 --> 00:44:52.410
all those sorts of things.

00:44:52.410 --> 00:44:53.790
That's fine.

00:44:53.790 --> 00:44:58.770
What I want to do is think
about it instead as a filter.

00:44:58.770 --> 00:45:01.590
So imagine the Bode plot.

00:45:01.590 --> 00:45:04.680
The Bode plot is good, right?

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:06.900
So imagine the Bode
plot representation

00:45:06.900 --> 00:45:11.080
for the RC low-pass filter.

00:45:11.080 --> 00:45:13.950
So the RC low-pass
filter has a single pole.

00:45:13.950 --> 00:45:16.410
The pole is at the
frequency 1 over RC.

00:45:16.410 --> 00:45:18.740
Minus 1 over RC.

00:45:18.740 --> 00:45:20.070
Bode plot looks like so.

00:45:20.070 --> 00:45:23.610
Magnitude has an asymptote
at low frequencies

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:24.510
that is a constant.

00:45:24.510 --> 00:45:27.540
At high frequencies, it's
sloping with minus 1.

00:45:27.540 --> 00:45:31.670
Or, as we would say,
minus 20 dB per decade.

00:45:31.670 --> 00:45:33.597
And it has some sort
of phase response.

00:45:33.597 --> 00:45:34.930
Low frequencies, the phase is 0.

00:45:34.930 --> 00:45:39.120
High frequencies, the
phase lags by pi over 2.

00:45:39.120 --> 00:45:42.750
But now, let's think about
exciting it with a square wave.

00:45:42.750 --> 00:45:45.750
Square wave is what we've
been thinking about.

00:45:45.750 --> 00:45:51.450
Square wave has a harmonic
structure that falls with k.

00:45:51.450 --> 00:45:58.800
So if we represent k equals
1, 3, 5, 7, 9 on a log scale,

00:45:58.800 --> 00:46:02.110
falling with k is
a linear slope.

00:46:02.110 --> 00:46:04.980
So this linear decrease
in amplitude height

00:46:04.980 --> 00:46:08.190
is the reciprocal over here.

00:46:08.190 --> 00:46:10.970
It's the idea of a log, right?

00:46:10.970 --> 00:46:13.310
So we can represent the
signal, the square wave,

00:46:13.310 --> 00:46:16.920
by this amplitude spectrum.

00:46:16.920 --> 00:46:18.480
How big are the
components at all

00:46:18.480 --> 00:46:19.500
of the different frequencies?

00:46:19.500 --> 00:46:21.375
Well, there's only a
discrete number of them.

00:46:21.375 --> 00:46:23.550
There's the k equals 1
one, the k equals 3 one,

00:46:23.550 --> 00:46:25.320
the k equals 5 one, et cetera.

00:46:25.320 --> 00:46:27.270
Each one represented
by a straight line.

00:46:27.270 --> 00:46:30.830
And they all have phase of minus
pi over 2 because of the j.

00:46:34.100 --> 00:46:38.030
Now, if you were to
choose the base frequency

00:46:38.030 --> 00:46:47.200
for the square wave so that
2 pi over capital T omega 0

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:52.880
is small compared to
the cutoff frequency

00:46:52.880 --> 00:46:56.400
for the low-pass
filter, what would

00:46:56.400 --> 00:47:04.380
be the effect on these
amplitudes of this filter?

00:47:04.380 --> 00:47:05.880
Well, the magnitude is 1.

00:47:05.880 --> 00:47:09.360
So if you go to arbitrarily
low frequencies,

00:47:09.360 --> 00:47:11.580
the magnitude is
arbitrarily close to 1.

00:47:11.580 --> 00:47:14.730
If the phase is arbitrarily
close to pi over 2,

00:47:14.730 --> 00:47:15.480
what would happen?

00:47:18.702 --> 00:47:20.910
Excuse me, the phase would
be arbitrarily close to 0.

00:47:20.910 --> 00:47:21.570
Sorry.

00:47:21.570 --> 00:47:23.920
I'm supposed to be going
to very low frequencies.

00:47:23.920 --> 00:47:27.540
If I go to very low
frequencies, the phase is 0.

00:47:27.540 --> 00:47:29.850
If the amplitude is
arbitrary close to 1,

00:47:29.850 --> 00:47:31.860
the phase is
arbitrarily close to 0.

00:47:31.860 --> 00:47:34.557
And if the input is represented
by the red lines, what's

00:47:34.557 --> 00:47:35.640
the output represented by?

00:47:38.930 --> 00:47:42.420
Same red lines, right?

00:47:42.420 --> 00:47:46.010
Each red line is
multiplied by 1 at angle 0.

00:47:48.530 --> 00:47:51.290
So the output has the
same shape as the input.

00:47:54.370 --> 00:48:00.730
If, however, I shift the
period to be shorter,

00:48:00.730 --> 00:48:04.620
so that omega 0
is higher, then I

00:48:04.620 --> 00:48:07.050
can have some of the
higher frequencies

00:48:07.050 --> 00:48:12.070
fall into the region
of sloping magnitude.

00:48:12.070 --> 00:48:15.340
I can have some of the
phases fall into the region

00:48:15.340 --> 00:48:19.480
where the phase is
minus pi over 2.

00:48:19.480 --> 00:48:22.030
The way to think about
it is the fundamental

00:48:22.030 --> 00:48:26.380
is still going through the place
with unity gain phase of 0.

00:48:26.380 --> 00:48:29.080
The basic shape is determined
by the fundamental.

00:48:29.080 --> 00:48:32.390
The basic shape comes through.

00:48:32.390 --> 00:48:34.610
But now the high frequencies
are being altered

00:48:34.610 --> 00:48:37.130
and their phase relationship
is being altered.

00:48:37.130 --> 00:48:41.360
And that's why the
shape is different.

00:48:41.360 --> 00:48:45.110
If you go to still
higher frequencies,

00:48:45.110 --> 00:48:48.560
more of the components
are filtered.

00:48:48.560 --> 00:48:51.650
Each component gets sent
through the frequency response.

00:48:51.650 --> 00:48:54.290
And its amplitude and phase
are modified appropriately.

00:48:54.290 --> 00:48:57.680
And if you go to extremely
high frequencies,

00:48:57.680 --> 00:49:03.670
then all of the
magnitudes are multiplied

00:49:03.670 --> 00:49:05.800
by this sloping down line.

00:49:05.800 --> 00:49:09.340
We turn k convergence-- we
turn the reciprocal in k

00:49:09.340 --> 00:49:11.770
into a reciprocal on k squared.

00:49:11.770 --> 00:49:15.650
Where have we seen that before?

00:49:15.650 --> 00:49:20.000
That was the decomposition
for the triangle wave.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:24.450
So the answer comes out
looking like a triangle wave.

00:49:24.450 --> 00:49:27.560
The point being that
in addition to thinking

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:30.130
about how the system works in
terms of feeding frequencies

00:49:30.130 --> 00:49:31.550
through it, now
we think about how

00:49:31.550 --> 00:49:36.460
signals work by breaking
them up into frequency parts.

00:49:36.460 --> 00:49:39.370
And the whole system
then is reduced to,

00:49:39.370 --> 00:49:43.010
how does the system
modify that component?

00:49:43.010 --> 00:49:44.920
So that gives rise to
the idea of thinking

00:49:44.920 --> 00:49:48.490
about the system as a filter.

00:49:48.490 --> 00:49:50.830
LTI systems do not
generate new frequencies.

00:49:50.830 --> 00:49:53.200
All they do is modify
the amplitude and phase

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:54.550
of existing frequencies.

00:49:54.550 --> 00:49:57.100
If you enumerate all of
the existing frequencies,

00:49:57.100 --> 00:49:58.960
you can just go
through them one by one

00:49:58.960 --> 00:50:00.700
and figure out
how they come out.

00:50:00.700 --> 00:50:04.062
And that's an equivalent way of
thinking about an LTI system.

00:50:04.062 --> 00:50:05.770
And that's the kind
of a focus that we'll

00:50:05.770 --> 00:50:09.100
use in the remaining
part of the course.

00:50:09.100 --> 00:50:10.350
OK,

